    "modelAnswer": "The debate over whether public funds should be allocated to outer space exploration or redirected towards pressing terrestrial issues is a highly contentious one. While venturing into the cosmos undeniably yields significant technological and scientific dividends, I firmly believe that addressing humanity's fundamental needs on Earth must be the primary focus of government expenditure.\n\nProponents of space exploration argue that investing in extraterrestrial research is crucial for human advancement. The monumental financial commitments required for space agencies have historically catalysed groundbreaking technological innovations. For instance, satellite technology, which currently underpins global communication, weather forecasting, and navigation systems, was a direct byproduct of the space race. Furthermore, some scientists assert that exploring other planets is a necessary insurance policy for the long-term survival of the human race, potentially offering new habitats or resources in the event of a catastrophic global disaster.\n\nConversely, many argue that allocating billions of dollars to outer space is morally unjustifiable when Earth is fraught with severe crises. Millions of people currently lack access to basic necessities such as clean drinking water, adequate healthcare, and primary education. It is argued that redirecting astronomical space budgets towards poverty alleviation, medical research, and renewable energy infrastructure would yield immediate and tangible improvements in the quality of life for the global population. In this view, solving the acute challenges of climate change and famine should ethically precede the exploration of barren planets.\n\nIn my opinion, although space exploration has unequivocally driven technological progress, the sheer scale of current global emergencies necessitates a reprioritisation of government spending. It is highly paradoxical to search for habitable environments millions of miles away while simultaneously neglecting the ecological and social collapse of our own planet.\n\nIn conclusion, while the pursuit of cosmic discovery offers long-term scientific benefits, governments have a fundamental obligation to prioritise the immediate welfare of their citizens. Therefore, the bulk of state funding should be channelled into resolving critical terrestrial issues before casting our ambitions to the stars."
