    "minWords": 250,
    "modelAnswer": "The rapid advancement of technology has ushered in an era where automated systems and artificial intelligence are increasingly performing tasks previously undertaken by humans. While some argue that this trend will inevitably lead to widespread unemployment and subsequent societal unrest, others maintain that it will generate unprecedented opportunities and elevate global living standards. In my opinion, although the short-term disruption to the labour market is a valid concern, the long-term benefits of automation far outweigh its drawbacks, provided that adequate retraining initiatives are implemented.\n\nProponents of the view that automation poses a threat to society primarily point to the displacement of workers. Manufacturing, logistics, and even administrative sectors are witnessing human labour being replaced by algorithms and robotics. Consequently, individuals whose skills become redundant may face prolonged periods of unemployment, leading to financial hardship. This economic marginalisation can, in turn, precipitate wider social issues, including increased crime rates and widening income inequality, particularly for blue-collar workers who might lack the resources to pivot to new career paths seamlessly.\n\nConversely, those who champion automation emphasise its potential to drive economic efficiency and foster innovation. By delegating repetitive and physically demanding tasks to machines, human capital is freed up to focus on creative, strategic, and interpersonal pursuits. Furthermore, automation drastically reduces production costs, which can lower the prices of essential goods and services, thereby improving the overall standard of living. The advent of new technologies also inherently creates entirely new industries and job categories, such as robotics maintenance, data analysis, and software engineering, which were inconceivable a few decades ago.\n\nI firmly believe that the integration of automated systems is an inevitable and largely positive progression for humanity. While the transitional phase undeniably presents challenges for certain demographics, these can be effectively mitigated through proactive government policies, such as subsidised vocational training and robust educational reforms. Ultimately, by eliminating the drudgery of menial labour, automation empowers society to achieve higher levels of productivity and intellectual fulfilment.\n\nIn conclusion, rather than fearing the rise of automated technologies, society should embrace them while simultaneously constructing robust social safety nets to support displaced workers during the transition."
