    "modelAnswer": "In recent decades, significant advancements in healthcare and living standards have led to a steady increase in life expectancy globally, resulting in a rapidly ageing population in many nations. While this demographic shift presents substantial economic challenges, it also offers invaluable social and cultural benefits to society.\n\nThe most evident disadvantage of an ageing population is the economic strain it places on a country. As the proportion of elderly citizens grows, the size of the active workforce inevitably shrinks. This demographic imbalance leads to a reduction in income tax revenues for the government, simultaneously accompanied by a surge in public expenditure on pensions, specialized healthcare, and social services. Consequently, a disproportionate financial burden is placed on the younger, working-age population. For instance, countries such as Japan and Italy are currently grappling with escalating healthcare costs and have been forced to gradually increase the state retirement age to prevent economic stagnation.\n\nConversely, an older demographic yields profound social advantages that are often overlooked. Elderly individuals possess a wealth of life experience and professional expertise that can be passed down to younger generations, fostering a more stable and knowledgeable society. Furthermore, many retirees actively contribute to their communities through volunteer work and civic participation. Within the family unit, grandparents frequently assume vital childcare responsibilities, which not only facilitates emotional development in children but also enables both parents to participate fully in the workforce, indirectly stimulating economic productivity.\n\nIn conclusion, an ageing population undoubtedly imposes severe financial and structural pressures on national economies, primarily through escalating healthcare and pension costs. However, the multifaceted social contributions of the elderly, ranging from community volunteering to essential family support, constitute a significant advantage. Governments must therefore implement proactive policies, such as promoting healthy ageing and flexible working conditions, to mitigate the economic drawbacks while harnessing the positive aspects of this demographic evolution."
