    "modelAnswer": "The ethical implications of keeping animals in captivity have been a subject of intense debate for many years. While some individuals argue that confining animals to zoos is an inherently cruel practice, others maintain that these institutions play an indispensable role in the conservation of endangered species. In my opinion, although poorly managed facilities can undoubtedly cause animal suffering, strictly regulated, modern zoos are crucial for global wildlife preservation.\n\nOn the one hand, opponents of zoos highlight the undeniable psychological and physical toll that captivity can take on wild animals. In traditional enclosures, animals are completely deprived of their natural habitats, complex social structures, and vast territories. This restriction can precipitate unnatural, repetitive behaviours known as zoochosis, where animals pace or self-harm due to chronic stress and boredom. Furthermore, critics argue that the primary purpose of many zoological parks is human entertainment rather than animal welfare, effectively commodifying sentient beings for commercial gain. From this perspective, locking animals in cages is a fundamental violation of their natural rights.\n\nOn the other hand, contemporary zoological institutions serve as vital sanctuaries for species facing the imminent threat of extinction. Rapid deforestation, climate change, and relentless poaching have decimated natural habitats worldwide, leaving many animals with no safe refuge in the wild. In response, modern zoos facilitate sophisticated captive breeding programmes that are essential for maintaining genetic diversity. Successful initiatives have even reintroduced species back into their native environments, such as the Arabian Oryx and the California condor. Additionally, these institutions provide invaluable educational opportunities, fostering a sense of environmental stewardship in the public and raising critical funding for global conservation efforts.\n\nIn conclusion, while the confinement of wild animals raises valid ethical concerns regarding their welfare and natural freedoms, the reality of our rapidly degrading natural world makes zoos a necessary conservation tool. Therefore, I believe that as long as they prioritise stringent welfare standards and scientific research over mere entertainment, zoos remain a vital mechanism for protecting our planet's most vulnerable species."
